         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="fig1">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0010" view="all">Location of the Northeast Indian state of Manipur in the Eastern Himalayan Region (a) and its landuse land cover (LULC) (b). Source: <ce:cross-ref refid="bib28" id="crosref0880">NRSC, 2019</ce:cross-ref>. Landuse/Land Cover database on 1:50,000 scale, Natural Resources Census.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0015">Fig. 1</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr1"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig2">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0015" view="all">Vertical distribution of total carbon (a), total organic carbon (b), and total inorganic carbon (c) along the soil depth across land uses in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur). Layer mean of land uses followed by different letters (a–g) in horizontal direction are significantly different at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05 (DMRT: Duncan's Multiple Range Test). Interaction between land use and soil depth for total carbon, organic carbon, and inorganic carbon is significant at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001. DFC: Dense forest cover, NAF: Non leguminous agroforestry, LAF: Leguminous agroforestry, WHF: Woody horticultural fruits, NHF: Non woody horticultural fruits, ALS: Agriculture lowland system, AUS: Agriculture upland system.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0020">Fig. 2</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr2"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig3">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0020" view="all">Vertical distribution of different organic carbon pools (a) Pool-1(C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>: very labile); (b) Pool-2 (C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>: labile); (c) Pool-3 (C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>: less labile); and (d) Pool-4 (C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>: non-labile) across land uses along the soil profile depth in the in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur). Layer mean of land uses followed by different letters (a–g) in horizontal direction are significantly different at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05 (DMRT: Duncan's Multiple Range Test). Interaction between land use and soil depth for total carbon, organic carbon, and inorganic carbon is significant at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001. DFC: Dense forest cover, NAF: Non leguminous agroforestry, LAF: Leguminous agroforestry, WHF: Woody horticultural fruits, NHF: Non woody horticultural fruits, ALS: Agriculture lowland system, AUS: Agriculture upland system.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0025">Fig. 3</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr3"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig4">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0025" view="all">Vertical distribution of soil microbial properties (a) SMBC, (b) DHA, and (c) APA under different land uses in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur). SMBC: Soil microbial biomass carbon, DHA: Dehydrogenase activity; APA: Acid phosphatase. Layer mean of land uses followed by different letters (a–e) in horizontal direction are significantly different at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05 (DMRT: Duncan's Multiple Range Test). Interaction between land use and soil depth for total carbon, organic carbon, and inorganic carbon is significant at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001. DFC: Dense forest cover, NAF: Non leguminous agroforestry, LAF: Leguminous agroforestry, WHF: Woody horticultural fruits, NHF: Non woody horticultural fruits, ALS: Agriculture lowland system, AUS: Agriculture upland system.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0030">Fig. 4</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr4"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig5">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0030" view="all">Principal component analysis ordination diagram showing distribution of seven land uses along the first two axis based on (a) surface and (b) subsurface soils (0.15–1.0 m) for 15 variables (particle size, BD, pH, C, and microbial properties) in the studied area. DFC: Dense forest cover, NAF: Non leguminous agroforestry, LAF: Leguminous agroforestry, WHF: Woody horticultural fruits, NHF: Non woody horticultural fruits, ALS: Agriculture lowland system, AUS: Agriculture upland system, PWA: Profile weighted average, TC: Total Carbon, TOC: Total organic carbon, Pool 1, Pool 2, Pool 3 and Pool 4 stand for very labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>), labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>), less labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>) and non labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>), SMBC: soil microbial biomass carbon, DHA: Dehydrogenase, APA: Acid phosphatase, ρb: Bulk Density.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0035">Fig. 5</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr5"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig6">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0035" view="all">Stratification Ratio (SR) of <ce:bold>(a)</ce:bold> Total Organic Carbon (TOC) and <ce:bold>(b)</ce:bold> Very Labile Caron (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>) in different underlying soil layers, and surface soil (Sur: 0.0–0.15 m depth) to the weighted average of subsurface soil (Sub: 0.15–1.0 m depth) under different land uses in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur). The bars represent standard deviations. Duncan's Multiple Range Test (DMRT) values with the different lowercase letters within the stratification ratio are significantly different at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05. NB: SR1:0.0–0.15/0.15–0.30 m, SR2: 0.0–0.15/0.30–0.45 m, SR3: 0.0–0.15/0.45–0.60 m, SR4: 0.0–0.15/0.60–0.80 m, SR5: 0.0–0.15/0.80–1.0 m (bottom most layers), SR6: 0.0–0.15/0.15–1.0 m (weighted sub surface).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0040">Fig. 6</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr6"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig7">
               <ce:label>Fig. 7</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0040" view="all">Soil degradation Index (DI) in surface soil (L1: 0.0–0.15 m), intermediate sub soil layers (L2-L6) and weighted average of subsurface soil (0.15–0.10 m) under cultivated land uses in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur). The bars represent standard deviations. Duncan's Multiple Range Test Values (DMRT) with the different lowercase letters within the degradation ratios are significantly different at <ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05. See <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0885">Table 1</ce:cross-ref> for abbreviations. Note: Surface soil (L1: 0.0–0.15 m), Subsurface layers (L2-L6: 0–0.15 m, 0.15–0.30 m, 0.30–0.45 m, 0.45–0.60 m, 0.60–80 m, 0.80–1.0 m) and weighted average of subsurface layer: 0.15–1.0 m depth).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0045">Fig. 7</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr7" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479721019484/gr7"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" id="tbl1" frame="topbot" colsep="0" rowsep="0">
               <ce:label>Table 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0045">
                  <ce:simple-para id="tspara0010" view="all">Vertical distribution of sand, silt, clay, soil bulk density (ρb), and pH across land use systems in the surface and subsurface soils in the foothills of Eastern Himalaya (Manipur).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
