                     <sa:country>India</sa:country>
                  </sa:affiliation>
               </ce:correspondence>
            </ce:author-group>
            <ce:date-received day="28" month="5" year="2021"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="26" month="9" year="2021"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="29" month="9" year="2021"/>
            <ce:abstract xml:lang="en" id="abs0010" view="all" class="author"><ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0010" view="all">The conversion of primary forests to cultivation brings a significant change in soil carbon (C) forms. In the foothills of the Eastern Himalayan Region of India (Manipur), such conversions are prevalent. However, little is known about the response of C forms, particularly in deep soil, to land use conversion in the region. We evaluated changes in soil C forms (total organic, inorganic, and pools) and microbiological properties (up to 1.0 m depth) mediated by C when the 45-year-old forest had been cultivated for 18–25 years. The cultivated land uses were tree-based agroforestry (LAF: legumes, NAF: non-legumes), horticultural fruits (WHF: woody, NHF: non-wood, mainly vegetables), and paddy agriculture system (AUS: upland, ALS: lowlands). Forest conversion significantly (p &lt; 0.05) decreased the total carbon (TC) in the surface soil (0.0–0.15 m) from 4.88 % to 3.04–3.93 % in the tree-based land uses (LAF, NAF, and WHF). TC further declined to 2.05–2.81 % under seasonal crops (NHF, AUS, and ALS). Seasonal crop cultivation also caused a higher decline in microbial biomass carbon, soil enzymes, and carbon pools (active and passive) than the tree-based land use with the soil depth. The vertical distribution of C in the soil profile was inconsistent: organic C (including C pools) decreased, while inorganic C increased. The profile TC stock to a depth of 1.0 m in the forest was 358.8 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, of which 81 % were organic C, and 19 % were inorganic C. In comparison with forest soil, total soil C stocks (organic and inorganic) decreased more (−44.1 to −55.1 %) in seasonal crops than in tree-based (−15.4 to −36.3 %) land uses. The degradation index (DI) also confirmed that seasonal crop cultivation caused a larger decline in surface soil quality (DI: −423 % to −623 %) than tree-based land use (DI: −243 % to −317 %). The topsoil (up to 0.45 m) of seasonal crops was more degraded than that of the subsoil (&gt;0.45 m–1.0 m). Forests converted to seasonal cultivation (upland rice and vegetables) caused higher degradation of soil C forms and overall soil health in the Himalayan foothills of northeastern India. We suggest the promotion of Agroforestry based on legumes (<ce:italic>Parkia</ce:italic> spp.) and woody fruits (mango/citrus/guava) in the uplands to minimize soil C degradation while ensuring nutritional security in the hill agro-ecosystems of the Indian Himalayas.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords xml:lang="en" id="kwrds0010" view="all" class="keyword">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0020">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0010">
                  <ce:text>Land use conversion</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0015">
                  <ce:text>Vertical distribution</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0020">
                  <ce:text>Total carbon stock</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0025">
                  <ce:text>Carbon pools</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0030">
                  <ce:text>Degradation index</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0035">
                  <ce:text>Mountain ecosystem</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0025">1. Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Land use conversion is one of the main drivers of global environmental imbalance, greatly contributing to climate change, loss of ecosystem services, and changes in soil carbon (C) forms (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib42" id="crosref0040">Srinivasarao et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0045">Maharjan et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Conversion of natural forest to agriculture and agricultural intensification contribute to the loss of soil organic C (SOC), alter microbial biomass and its activities, and affect soil quality (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib19" id="crosref0050">Lagomarsino et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, there is a growing global interest in the assessment of land use and management effects on soil properties in particular C forms (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0055">Maharjan et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Fractionation of organic C stock into labile and non-labile pools depending on their varying residence time helps in a better understanding of the mechanism by which C is stabilized or lost (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0060">Sarkar et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Labile pool (active) is easily decomposable, sensitive to land use change, and influences the nutrient cycle to maintain soil health and productivity (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0065">Haynes, 2005</ce:cross-ref>). The non-labile pool (passive) is highly recalcitrant and relatively resistant to microbial decomposition (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib51" id="crosref0070">Weil et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>). Hence, it contributes to the build-up of total organic C stock (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0075">Chan et al., 2001</ce:cross-ref>). Soil microbial biomass C (SMBC) acts as a sensitive indicator, since responds more rapidly to soil management and disturbances than the native C concentration (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib25" id="crosref0080">Mganga et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Soil enzymes play a crucial role in organic matter (OM) decomposition and nutrient cycling and thus, are associated with SMBC (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0085">Yao et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Eastern Himalaya Region (EHR) of India, set in a mountain ecosystem, is known for its significant forest (broadleaf and conifer) cover, representing a biodiversity hotspot, with rugged, and largely inaccessible terrains (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0090">Choudhury et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Over the past many decades, the region had experienced large-scale deforestation and associated land degradation attributed to the expansion of traditional agriculture (shifting and settled cultivation, burning of vegetation, and cultivation along the slopes). This resulted in a decline in forest cover to &lt;63 % geographical area (GA: 26.2 M ha, Northeast India) while scrubs from forest degradation increased from marginal to significant areas (&gt;11.8 % GA). Similarly, conversion of forests to agriculture (shifting and settled-up &amp; lowlands) also occupy a considerable area (&gt;14 % GA) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib28" id="crosref0095">NRSC, 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0100">Choudhury et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Such conversion of land use caused a significant decline in SOC, essential nutrients, microbial properties, and more importantly soil quality deterioration (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0105">Devi and Choudhury, 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0110">Lungmuana et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0115">2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0120" refid="bib8">Choudhury and Mandal, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). In the predominant marginal intensive agriculture of the region, periodic replenishment of soil nutrients from organic or inorganic sources is limited. Therefore, C forms are the backbone in sustaining agricultural production to meet the food requirements of the region. Realizing the importance of soil C, studies on the mapping of C status (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib9" id="crosref0125">Choudhury et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>), land use interaction on C forms (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0130">Devi and Choudhury, 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0135">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>), and recently few studies on C pools and microbial properties limited to shifting cultivation were carried out in the region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0140">Sarkar et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0145">Lungmuana et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0150">2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0155">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). However, most of these studies were limited to topsoil (0–0.45 m depth), although the amount of soil C stored below 0.30 m, even beyond 1.0 m depth is significant to many ecosystems (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib18" id="crosref0160">Jobbágy and Jackson, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Similarly, available information on the vertical distribution of C forms and soil enzymes in soil profiles (≥1.0 m depth) is lacking in the region. In addition, marginal information is available on how C forms respond to the conversion of forests to cultivation.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">We conducted the study in the foothills of the EHR of India (Manipur state), which was traditionally covered with primary (&gt;45 years old) dense mixed forests (DFC). In the past few decades, complementary land use practices like agroforestry and horticulture along sloping uplands were introduced as an alternative to the low productive and highly unsustainable traditional agriculture (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0165">Devi and Choudhury, 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0170">Lungmuana et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Also, paddy based crop intensification in the up and lowlands were popularized to meet the food demands of the inhabitants. Our study site was one of those few sites in the region, where forests were converted to agroforestry (legumes/non legumes), horticulture (woody/non woody), and agricultural production systems. We hypothesized that this conversion from primary forests to cultivated land uses for long periods (18–25 years) might have brought in significant changes in different levels of C forms. At the same time, we assumed that the quality of soil might have degraded with this conversion. Therefore, we studied the effect of these established alternative tree based (e.g. leguminous and non-leguminous agroforestry, woody horticultural fruits) and seasonal crop cultivation (up and lowland agriculture, and non-woody vegetable based horticulture) on soil carbon forms (total, organic, inorganic, pools, and stock) and microbiological properties up to 1.0 m soil profile depth. To test the hypothesis, we compared the results with the primary dense forests of 45 years old as reference.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0030">Materials and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.1" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Geo-environmental setup</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">The study site was located in the foothills of EHR of India (Manipur) and lies between 24<ce:sup loc="post">°</ce:sup> 31′ 51.7″ to 24<ce:sup loc="post">°</ce:sup> 31′ 30.59″ N latitude and 93<ce:sup loc="post">°</ce:sup> 56′ 32.06″ to 94<ce:sup loc="post">°</ce:sup> 08′ 30.4″ E longitude at an elevation range of 785–850 m from mean sea level (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0175">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>). The experimental site was developed in a moderately sloping forest land with marginal slope variation ranging from 16 to 24 % across the land uses. Forest and tree-based land uses were comparable in slope variation (22–24 %) while seasonal crops (including terraced paddy) were cultivated at 16–21 % slope. Soils were originated from the sedimentary rocks and the parent materials belong to sandstone and shale of <ce:italic>Disang</ce:italic> (Eocene) and <ce:italic>Barail</ce:italic> (Oligocene) group (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib38" id="crosref0180">Sen et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>). The area experiences subtropical humid to per humid climate with an annual average rainfall of 1855 mm and 21.9 °C air temperature. More than 60 % (1113 mm) of the annual rainfall is received in the monsoon months (JJAS: June to September) followed by 39 % (723 mm) in pre-monsoon months (MAM: March to May). Post-monsoon months (ONDJF: October to February) generally remain rainless and dry.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.2" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Land use and land cover (LULC)</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">The mixed dense forest was the primary land use system in the area for more than four decades. Due to the lack of available lands for cultivation, large scale conversion of forests to traditional agriculture along sloping uplands had been continued (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0185">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). This resulted in a decline of forest area from &gt;80 % to 67 % of 2.23 M ha GA of Manipur, while degraded scrubland increased to 25 % GA in recent times (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib28" id="crosref0190">NRSC, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). A large patch (0.5 km by 0.4 km) of primary forests (&gt;45 years old) still exists near the converted (cultivated) land uses. We selected six 18–25 years old cultivated land use systems (1.5–1.90 ha area each) along with primary forest as a reference. The selected seven land uses were (i) Dense forest cover (DFC) 45 years old with climax vegetation of <ce:italic>Litsea polyantha</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Castonopsis tribuloides,</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Albizia chinensis</ce:italic>, (ii) Intercropped Non leguminous Agroforestry (NAF) 20 years old under <ce:italic>Jatropha curcas</ce:italic> L. and <ce:italic>Bambusa arundinacea</ce:italic>, (iii) Intercropped leguminous Agroforestry (LAF) 20 years old with <ce:italic>Parkia roxburghii G.</ce:italic>, (iv) Intercropped woody horticultural fruits (WHF) 18 years old under <ce:italic>Mangifera indica</ce:italic> L., <ce:italic>Citrus</ce:italic> spp. <ce:italic>and Psidium guajava</ce:italic> L. (v) Non-woody horticultural fruits (NHF) 18 years old (mostly vegetables), (vi) Agricultural lowland system (ALS) 25 years old under paddy (<ce:italic>Oryza sativa</ce:italic> L.) –fallow/pulses/oilseeds, and (vii) Agricultural upland system (AUS) 25 years old under upland rice (<ce:italic>Oryza sativa</ce:italic> L.) –fallow/pulses/oilseeds. More details about tree-based and intercrops/mixed crops and nutrient management practices maintained over the years are given in Supp. <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0195">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl1"/>.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0050">Soil sampling protocol</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">We selected 28 quadrate measuring 20 m × 20 m each (four quadrate for each land use) by random stratified sampling method (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib50" id="crosref0200">Webster and Lark, 2012</ce:cross-ref>), and exposed soil profiles up to a depth of 1.0 m in each corner of the quadrate. To capture the lateral variation of soil carbon distribution in the profiles, we collected soil samples at six vertical layers (L1-L6), since the lateral variation of soil properties including organic C varies within a single pedon (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib43" id="crosref0205">Stolt et al., 1993</ce:cross-ref>). The depth of each layer was 0–0.15 m (L1), 0.15–0.30 m (L2), 0.30–0.45 m (L3), 0.45–0.60 m (L4), 0.60–0.80 m (L5), and 0.80–1.00 m (L6), respectively. Samples from each corner of the quadrate were layer-wise mixed (L1+L1+L1+L1 = L1) to get depth-wise one composite sample for each profile. We collected a total of 168 soil samples (6 depths × 4 sites × 7 land uses, 24 samples per land use) from the surface (0–0.15 m) up to a depth of 1.0 m during post-monsoon dry months (November to December 2017).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0055">Laboratory analysis of soil carbon, carbon pools, and microbial properties</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">Soil bulk density (ρb) was measured for each layer across quadrate using a core sampler (5.15 cm height and 4.7 cm diameter) and oven drying at 104 ± 1 °C. Half of the pre-processed (removal of debris, stones, roots, etc.) samples were immediately stored in sealed polythene bags at freezing temperature. The remaining half was air-dried, grounded, and passed through a 2.0 mm sieve. These sieved samples were then analyzed for pH (at 1:2.5 soil: water) with Digital pH meter 335 (Systronics, India) and particle size distribution by international pipette method (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0210">Page et al., 1982</ce:cross-ref>). For determination of soil C forms, sieved (2.0 mm) samples were again passed through 0.5 mm mesh and used for further analysis. Total carbon (TC) was determined by using PC controlled Carbon-Sulfur analyzer (ELTRA CS 580 A “Helios” Carbon - Sulfur Analyzer) with a vertical resistance furnace. Total Inorganic Carbon (TIC) content was measured with the TIC module attached to this analyzer.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Different pools of total organic carbon (TOC) were determined by the modified Walkley and Black method as described by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0215">Chan et al. (2001)</ce:cross-ref> using 5, 10, and 20 ml concentrated (36.0 N) H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf> that resulted in three acid-aqueous solutions in the ratios of 0.5:1, 1:1, and 2:1 corresponding to 12.0, 18.0, and 24.0 N of H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>, respectively. This method allowed partitioning of TOC into the following four different pools as given below:</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">Pool 1: (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>, very labile) organic C oxidizable by 12.0 N H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Pool 2: (C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>, labile) the difference in C oxidizable by 18.0 N and 12.0 N H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Pool 3: (C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>, less labile) the difference in C oxidizable by 24.0 N and 18.0 N H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">Pool 4: (C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>, non labile) the difference between TOC and C oxidizable by 24.0 N H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>SO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> and C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf> together represent the active pool [Active pool = Σ (pool 1 + pool 2)] and C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf> and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> together represents the passive pool [Passive pool = Σ (pool 3 + pool 4)] of organic C in soils.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Soil microbial biomass carbon (SMBC) was determined by the chloroform fumigation extraction method (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib48" id="crosref0220">Vance et al., 1987</ce:cross-ref>) from the stored (at freezing temperature) undisturbed fresh sample. Soil dehydrogenase activity (DHA) was determined by the Triphenyl tetrazolium chloride (TTC) method given by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0225">Casida et al. (1964)</ce:cross-ref> and expressed as μg TPF g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> soil h<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Acid phosphatase (APA) and alkaline phosphatase enzymatic activities were analyzed with modified universal buffer (MUB, pH 6.5 and 11.0) using 0.05 M p-nitrophenyl phosphate disodium salt (0.025 M) as a substrate (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0230">Tabatabai and Bremmer, 1969</ce:cross-ref>). Measurements of the above mentioned enzymatic activities were performed by UV-VIS spectrophotometer (Spectroquant ® Prove 300, Germany).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.4" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0060">Estimation of soil profile C stock, stratification ratio (SR), and degradation index (DI)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Total Organic Carbon (TOC, %) was estimated from the differences between total carbon (TC) and total inorganic carbon (TIC). The carbon (C) stocks (TC, TOC, TIC, and pools expressed in Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) for each soil layer (L), total soil profile depth (up to 1.0 m), and profile weighted average (PWA) values were calculated using corresponding soil bulk density (ρb) values of each soil layer (L1-L6) following Eqs. <ce:cross-refs refid="fd1 fd2 fd3 fd4" id="crosrefs0010">(1)–(4)</ce:cross-refs>.<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd1">
                              <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si1.svg" alttext="Equation 1.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                    <mml:mi>s</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                    <mml:mi>f</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                    <mml:mi>e</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>h</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                    <mml:mi>s</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                    <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>e</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mi>h</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>ρ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>b</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                             <mml:msup>
                                                <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mn>3</mml:mn>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:msup>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>%</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
