                     </ce:para>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.4.1" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0065">Stratification ratio (SR)</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">SR is the value of a soil parameter at the overlying layer divided by the value at the underneath layer (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib31" id="crosref0235">Qua et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The SR of TOC is an efficient indicator of soil quality and its increase is related to the rate and amount of TOC sequestration (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0240">Franzluebbers, 2002</ce:cross-ref>). We calculated SRs of TOC and very labile C pool (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>) concentrations between surface (0–0.15 m) and all the five subsurface soil layers as SR1 (0–0.15/0.15–0.30 m), SR2 (0–0.15/0.30–0.45 m), SR3 (0–0.15/0.45–0.60 m), SR4 (0–0.15/0.60–0.80 m), and SR5 (0–0.15/0.80–1.0 m, bottom most layer), respectively.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.4.2" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0070">Soil degradation index (DI)</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">The effect of land use conversion on soil degradation was evaluated by computing DIs. The DI was constructed by comparing the soil properties (particle size distribution, available nutrients, bulk density, acidity, cation exchange capacity, soil C forms, microbial properties, etc.) under the converted (tree and seasonal crop-based) land uses with the reference land use (forest) that exists in steady-state condition (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib1" id="crosref0245">Adejuwon and Ekandea, 1988</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib15" id="crosref0250">Gebresamuel et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib31" id="crosref0255">Qua et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Depth wise (L1: surface soil of 0.0–0.15 m; L2-L6: subsurface soil layers of 0.15–0.30 m, 0.30–0.45 m, 0.45–0.60 m, 0.60–80 m, 0.80–1.0 m, respectively) mean value of individual soil property under each of the cultivated land use (NAF, LAF, WHF, NHF, AUS, and ALS) were compared with the mean value under forests for the corresponding depth. The relative deviation ( %) of parameters was computed following the DI procedure as given in Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd5" id="crosref0260">(5)</ce:cross-ref> (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib15" id="crosref0265">Gebresamuel et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). The summation of all the DI values for measured soil properties under each layer and land use provided a single cumulative DI and expressed as percent change (+ve or –ve values). The cumulated sum was used as an index of soil degradation to measure the effect of land use change from natural vegetation to converted land use types.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="fd5">
                                 <ce:label>(5)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si5.svg" alttext="Equation 5.">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi>D</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mfrac>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>U</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi>U</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mfrac>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">×</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mn>100</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>where DI is the degradation index represents relative change in soil property; X is the mean of soil properties in the converted (tree-based and seasonal crops) land uses; U is the mean of soil properties in undisturbed primary forest.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.5" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0075">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">All data were checked for normality of distribution, and the design of sampling across land use systems led to a simple balanced two way analysis of variance (ANOVA) with seven land uses and six soil depths (L1-L6) as factors/treatments. Soil C forms and microbial properties including enzymatic activities across land use systems and soil depths were compared by two-way ANOVAs followed by Duncan's Multiple Range Test (DMRT) at Post Hoc stage with 5 % probability level.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0080">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0085">Distribution of soil properties across land uses</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Surface (L1: 0–0.15 m) soils were sandy loam (SL) to sandy clay loam (SCL) in texture, while subsurface soil layers (L2-L6: 0.15–1.0 m) was sandy clay loam in texture (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0270">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). Significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) effect of land use on particle size distribution was visible only in the surface soil. Surface soils were relatively coarser (higher sand and low clay contents) in horticulture (WHF and NHF) and upland agriculture (AUS) than other land uses. In deeper depths (0.15 m onwards till 1.0 m depth), forests (DFC) and leguminous agroforestry (LAF) system had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher clay contents than the other land uses, particularly the seasonally cultivated land uses (NHF, ALS, and AUS) (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0275">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). In general, subsurface soil layers (L2-L6) among the land uses were comparable in sand contents. Soils across land use and soil depth were mostly acidic in reaction (pH: 4.76–6.22) and relatively higher acidic (pH: 4.86–5.22) in the forests along with the soil profile depth than other cultivated land uses except in NHF (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0280">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). Among the cultivated land uses, surface (L1, pH: 5.12) and sub-surface soil layers (L2 to L6) of vegetable based NHF were strongly acidic in reaction (pH: 4.68–4.95) while in lowland paddy based agriculture (ALS), soil pH was near neutral (pH &gt; 6.0) till 0.80 m sub-surface soil depth. However, there was an inconsistent trend in soil pH along with the soil depth from the surface to sub-surface soil layers up to 1.0 m depth across land uses. The soil bulk density (ρb) values increased inconsistently from the surface layer (L1) to the sub-surface layers across land uses. Forest soils were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) lower in bulk density values than the cultivated land uses, particularly seasonally cultivated agricultural land uses (ALS and AUS) in the entire soil depths (L1 to L6). Lowland paddy soils (ALS) were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in bulk density values in all the soil depths (L1-L6) compared to both tree-based and seasonally crop cultivated land uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0285">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). The interaction effect of land use on soil depth was non-significant for particle size distribution and bulk density values but was significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.0001) only for soil reaction (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0290">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0090">Vertical distribution of soil carbon across land use systems</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The total C (TC) contents varied widely in the surface (2.05 %–4.88 %) and subsurface soil layers (L2-L6: 1.03 %–3.49 %) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0295">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>a). Except for forest soils, the TC content decreased consistently along with the soil depth from the surface to the bottom-most sub-surface soil layer (L6) in the cultivated land uses. However, throughout the soil profile depth (from L1 to L6), forests (DFC) followed by woody horticulture (WHF) had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher TC content than other cultivated land uses. Tree-based leguminous agroforestry (LAF) had significantly higher TC contents till 0.30 m soil depth and below TC content was comparable with non-leguminous agroforestry (NAF) and seasonally cultivated lowland paddy (ALS) and vegetable-based NHF. Among the land uses, seasonally cultivated upland rice (AUS) recorded the lowest TC contents in the soil profile (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0300">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>a). Across the land uses, the TOC contributed 83–92 % of the TC in the surface layer (L1) but decreased to 55–74 % in the underlying immediate subsurface layer (L2) and then again increased to 60–85 % in the deeper subsurface soil layers (L3 to L6). The TIC contribution to TC was small in the surface (8–14 %) but increased to 26–45 % in L2 and then decreased to 15–40 % in the deeper subsurface soil layers (L3 to L6). The vertical distribution of total organic carbon (TOC) contents also reflected comparable trends with TC contents: forests followed by tree-based WHF and LAF had significantly higher TOC contents from surface till 0.80 m soil depth than the seasonally cultivated upland crops (AUS and NHF) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0305">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>b). Lowland paddy field (ALS) had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher soil profile TOC contents till 0.80 m depth than the seasonally cultivated AUS and NHF and was comparable with LAF in the subsurface soil layers (L2-L6) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0310">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>b). Unlike the consistent decrease in TOC contents vertically in the soil profile (from L1 to L6), distribution of TIC contents was twisted vertically and subsurface soil layers (L2-L4: 0.15–0.60 m depth) had higher TIC than the surface layer (L1). Though surface soil of forests recorded significantly (p &lt; 0.05) higher TIC, yet the vertical distribution was mostly irregular. Seasonally cultivated uplands (AUS and NHF) had significantly higher TIC contents than the lowland paddy and the tree-based agroforestry (LAF and NAF) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0315">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>c). Land use and soil depths had significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001) interaction effects on soil C forms (TC, TOC, and TIC contents) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0320">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0095">Vertical distribution of soil carbon pools across land use systems</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">Averaged over land uses, the very labile C pool (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>) contributed maximum (42 %) followed by non-labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>: 36.1 %), labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>: 12 %), and the least by less labile (C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>: 9.6 %) C pools to the TOC content in the surface soil (L1) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0325">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig3"/>a–d). The corresponding contribution of C pools along with the soil depth from immediate subsurface (L2) to the bottom-most soil layer (L6) varied from 28.1 to 38.8 % (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>), 37 %–49.6 % (C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>), 13.3 % (C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>), and 10.2 %–9.9 % (C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>), respectively. The C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> contribution (averaged over land uses) to TOC decreased consistently from 42.1 % (in L1) to 28.1 % (in L6) while a reverse trend of a regular increase in contribution of C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> from 36.1 % (in L1) to 49.6 % (in L6) along with the soil depth was observed (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0330">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a–d). Land use significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) influenced the amount and the proportion of different carbon pools along with the soil depth (L1-L6). The depth distribution of all the C-pools decreased irregularly from surface soil to the deeper subsurface soil layers (L5-L6) across land uses. Among the land uses, forest soil had a significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher amount of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>, and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> in the soil profile (L1-L6) and was comparable in C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> with tree-based woody horticulture (WHF). Tree-based WHF and leguminous AF (LAF) had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher amounts of all the fractions of C pools in the first 0.6 m soil depth (L1-L4) than the seasonally cultivated uplands (AUS and NHF). However, seasonally cultivated lowland soils (ALS) were an exception, recorded significantly higher amount of C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf> and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> than the cultivated uplands (AUS and NHF) and were comparable to tree-based WHF and LAF (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0335">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a–d). Upland agriculture (AUS) recorded the lowest amount of all the C pool fractions and was also significantly lower than the lowland agriculture (ALS) in the soil profile (L1-L6). Profile weighted average (P<ce:inf loc="post">WA</ce:inf>) C pool fractions particularly C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in the forest followed by tree-based land uses (WHF, LAF, and NAF) than the seasonally crop cultivated land uses (ALS, NHF, and AUS). The order of P<ce:inf loc="post">WA</ce:inf> C pools availability decreased as DFC &gt; WHF &gt; LAF &gt; NAF &gt; NAF &gt; ALS &gt; AUS (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0340">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl2"/>). The vertical distribution of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>, and C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf> revealed nearly a symmetric downward decreasing pattern in all the soil layers (L1-L6) across land uses, while C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf> showed a zigzag distribution pattern (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0345">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a–d). In the forest, C pool fractions were highly concentrated in the surface soil and decreased inconsistently along with the depth at steeper gradients. Comparable trends of steep decline from the surface to subsurface soil layers were observed only in LAF and WHF, while other cultivated land uses had a gradual inconsistent decreasing trend along with the depth (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0350">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a–d).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.4" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0100">Vertical distribution of SMBC and enzymatic activities across land use systems</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">The C-mediated soil microbial properties like SMBC, DHA, and APA measured in the surface soils (L1) varied widely from 79.0 to 291.9 μg C g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, 53.4–89.5 μg TPF g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, and 61.5–91.8 μ mol <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-NP g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, respectively across land uses. In the subsurface soil layers (L2-L6), they decreased significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) by many folds and recorded the lowest in L6 (SMBC: 3.8–21.0 μg C g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, DHA: 10–17.6 μg TPF g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, and APA: 8.5–25.8 μ mol <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-NP g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0355">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig4"/>a–c). The vertical distribution of SMBC in the soil profile were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in the forest soils till 0.30 m depth while in the deeper subsurface soils (L3-L6), they were comparable with tree-based WHF and NAF (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0360">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a). Leguminous agroforestry (LAF) had significantly higher SMBC than the forests in 0.30–0.60 m depth, beyond 0.60 m depth (L5-L6), it was comparable with forests. Vertical distribution of DHA reflected that the forest and LAF were comparable till 0.60 m soil depth and were significantly higher than the other land uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0365">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>b). The trend in depth distribution of APA along with the soil depth among the land uses was comparable with SMBC: forests soils had significantly higher APA till 0.45 m depth and beyound which, it was comparable with tree-based land uses (NAF, LAF, and WHF) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0370">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>c). Cultivation of seasonal crops (NHF, AUS, and ALS), more particularly upland paddy reduced the soil microbial properties (SMBC, DHA, and APA) significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) than the forests and tree-based land uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0375">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a). The microbial properties decreased inconsistently along with the soil depth vertically and the magnitude of decrease was abrupt in forest and tree-based land uses than the gradual decline observed in the seasonal crop cultivated land uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0380">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a–c). The interaction effect of land use and soil depth significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001) influenced the SMBC and enzymatic activities (DHA and APA) in the soil profile (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0385">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>). Estimation of profile weighted average (P<ce:inf loc="post">WA:</ce:inf> L1-L6) also confirmed that conversion of forest to cultivation resulted in a decrease in microbial properties in the following order: DFC &gt; LAF &gt; WHF &gt; NAF &gt; NHF &gt; ALS &gt; AUS (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0390">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a–c).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.5" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0105">Profile C and C pool stocks in different land use systems</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">Land use significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) influenced the estimated C stock (Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) forms in the soil profile (up to 1.0 m depth) (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl3" id="crosref0395">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl3"/>). The profile TC stock was the highest in forest soils (358.8 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and 81 % of TC was contributed by TOC (298.1 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) alone. The remaining 19 % (60.7 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) was contributed by TIC. On conversion of forests to cultivation, TC, TOC, and TIC stocks decreased by different magnitudes. The decline in TC and TOC was relatively less (−15.4 to −16.4 %) in WHF, moderate (−27.7 to −36.3 %) in ALS, LAF, and NAF but intensive (−44.1 to −55.1 %) in NHF and AUS. The lowest TC (191.3 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and TOC (133.7 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) stocks were estimated in AUS, while the lowest TIC stock (40.3 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) was estimated in LAF. Due to variability in TOC stock among the land uses, different fractions of C pool stocks also varied and forest soils were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in stocks of all the fractions of C-pool. The estimated C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> in different land uses followed the order of DFC ≥ WHF &gt; LAF &gt; NAF ≥ ALS &gt; AUS ≥ NHF (<ce:cross-refs refid="tbl2 tbl3" id="crosrefs0015">Tables 2 and 3</ce:cross-refs>). Similarly, conversion of forests to cultivation led to a decline in C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf> (−14.3 to −363 %), C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf> (−74.9 to −203.1 %), and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf> (−8.9 to −107.8 %) at different magnitudes. The seasonal rice cultivation (AUS) and vegetables (NHF) in uplands recorded the lowest stocks of C-pools. Interaction effects of land use and soil depth on total C stock (TC, TOC, TIC) and different C pools were significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001) (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl3" id="crosref0400">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.6" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.6</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0110">Correlation and multivariate analysis of soil parameters across land uses</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The soil parameters had a significant correlation with TOC (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl4" id="crosref0405">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl4"/>) except physical parameters (sand, silt, and ρ<ce:inf loc="post">b</ce:inf>) of soil. Soil C pools and enzymatic activities were significantly correlated (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.01) and were strongly influenced (positively) by clay contents. Similarly, a significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.01) correlation was observed between SMBC, C pools, and enzymatic activities (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl4" id="crosref0410">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>). The principal component analysis (PCA) ordination diagram demonstrated the distribution of seven land uses based on their association with 15 soil (surface: 0.0–0.15 m and sub-surface-weighted mean: 0.15–1.0 m depth) parameters as variables along the first two axes. The PCA axes 1 and 2 explained a total of 77.5 % and 18.1 %, respectively of the variance in surface soil properties. The corresponding variance explained for subsurface soil layers (weighted mean of 0.15–1.0 m) were 74.9 % and 17.5 %, respectively. Some significant associations were observed like C pools (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>, and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>), TOC, TIC, and microbial properties (SMBC, DHA, and APA) in surface soil (0–0.15 m) were more governed by the forest, while soil pH, silt, and bulk density values were governed by agriculture (AUS and ALS) than other land uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig5" id="crosref0415">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig5"/>a). Similarly, in the subsurface soils, forests controlled the C pools, TC, and TOC contents, while leguminous agroforestry (LAF) controlled the TC, clay, and microbial properties (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig5" id="crosref0420">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>b).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.7" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.7</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0115">Changes in the Stratification ratio (SR) of TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> under different land use systems</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Land use conversion significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) affected the stratification of both the TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> in different vertical soil layers (SR1-SR5) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0425">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig6"/>a–b). The TOC was highly stratified in the LAF across soil depths: ranging from 1.63 at SR1 to 3.62 SR5. The TOC was also significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) stratified in NAF in top 0.45 m soil depth (SR1 to SR2) while at deeper depths (&gt;0.45 m depth, SR3-SR4), a significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) stratification of TOC was observed in the forest soils than the cultivated land uses (except LAF) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0430">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>a). The stratification in TOC contents along the subsurface soil depths (L2-L5) in tree-based WHF was relatively less compared to LAF and NAF. Minimum stratification of TOC occurred in the lowland paddy soils (ALS) at the immediate sub-surface layer (SR1) and at deeper depths (SR2-SR5: 1.42–1.60), least SR was observed in the vegetable based upland system (NHF) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0435">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>a). Similarly, the depth distribution of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> was highly stratified in the top 0.30 m soil depth (SR1 and SR2) only in the LAF (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0440">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>b). In the subsurface soil layers (&gt;0.30 m–0.80 m depth), stratification of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> was significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in the forests and tree-based land uses (LAF, NAF, and WHF) than the crop cultivated land uses (ALS, NHF, and AUS). Despite having the lowest TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> contents in surface soils (L1) under upland agriculture (AUS), yet, SR5 at deeper subsoil (0.8–1.0 m) for both TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher in AUS than the other cultivated land uses. Next to AUS, forests, and tree-based land uses had significantly higher SR (SR5: 4.34–5.0) than the crop cultivated ALS and NHF (SR5:2.73–3.46) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0445">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>b). Alike TOC, stratification of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> is not land use sensitive in the underneath subsoil. Irrespective of land use type, a regular decline in TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> amount vertically in the soil profile (<ce:cross-refs refid="fig2 fig3" id="crosrefs0020">Figs. 2b and 3</ce:cross-refs>a), the SR (from SR1 to SR5) of both TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> gradually increased at different magnitudes along with the depth of soil profile. Moving from SR1 to SR5, the SR of TOC increased from 1.22 to 1.63 to 1.85–3.62 while the corresponding increase in SR of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> was from 1.17 to 2.04 to 2.73–5.58 (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig5" id="crosref0450">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>a–b).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0120">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0125">Impact of land use conversion on the vertical distribution of soil physical properties</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Land use change had a marginal influence on the particle size distribution and was evident from the similar textural classes (sandy clay loam) in the subsurface soil layers across land uses (except surface soil of seasonal crop cultivation). Soil texture is one of the most stable and static properties, it is not affected by management measures, except by soil erosion or human activities. Marginal variation in textural classes under different land uses confirmed that the soils were developed from homogeneous parent materials and soil-forming processes (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0455">Foth, 1990</ce:cross-ref>). However, significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) less clay content was measured in the surface soil of upland agriculture than other cultivated land uses. Cultivation in the sloping uplands of the region induced erosion and sedimentation/deposition of clay particles in the lowland paddy fields (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0460">Choudhury et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). In Semiarid northern China, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib53" id="crosref0465">Zhao et al. (2017)</ce:cross-ref> also reported that the conversion of natural vegetation into cropland resulted in coarseness in soil texture, mostly by erosion from the decline in surface cover. Similarly, the subsoil layers (L2-L6) had relatively higher clay content (26.9 %) than the surface soil (clay: 21.6 %). This could be attributed to the vertical translocation of clay by leaching and downward motions under the wet tropical condition in the region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0470">Moges et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). An increase in the depth distribution of the clay or even the illuviation of clay particles from the surface to the underground soil horizons (endopedon) in the studied region is common (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib34" id="crosref0475">Sahoo et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Similar observations of downward clay translocation and an increasing trend from the surface (0.0–0.20 m) to the subsurface (0.20–0.60 m) soils across land use (natural forest, agroforestry, and upland cultivated) were reported by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib47" id="crosref0480">Toru and Kibret (2019)</ce:cross-ref> in the Sub-tropical highland climate of Eastern Ethiopia (Hade's forest).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">Cultivation of paddy had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) increased soil bulk density values (ρ<ce:inf loc="post">b</ce:inf>) and were more compacted than the forest and other cultivated land uses. Intensive field traffic during wet tillage (puddling) operation and other associated cultural practices including clearing of surface residues in lowland paddy cultivation often increases the soil compaction in the subsurface soil depth (at 15–20 cm) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0485">Choudhury and Sigh, 2013</ce:cross-ref>). The soils under primary forest had significantly low bulk density values all throughout the soil profile depth than the cultivated land uses, probably due to higher SOC content from the decomposition of root biomass since organic matter improves soil aggregation (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib47" id="crosref0490">Toru and Kibret, 2019</ce:cross-ref>) and deeper root penetration (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0495">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). A similar observation of significantly low bulk density value in the natural forest compared to cultivated land use was reported by <ce:cross-ref id="optsOTrF7hsLV" refid="bib54">Teshome et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> in the western and central Highlands of Ethiopia. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib46" id="crosref0500">Tolimir et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> also reported that agricultural cultivation of forest lands increased the bulk density by 40 % in the surface (0.0–0.15 m) while 15 % in the subsurface (0.30–0.45 m) soil. Higher compaction (ρ<ce:inf loc="post">b</ce:inf> values) in the subsurface than the surface soils across cultivated uplands might be attributed to loosening of surface soil from repeated shallow tillage with limited (in tree-based system) operation (manual) confined to annual intercrops during cultivation practices and partly from higher root proliferation, SOC, and clay contents in surface soils (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0505">Moges et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib47" id="crosref0510">Toru and Kibret, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Soils were invariably acidic in reaction across the soil profile depth (till 1.0 m), mostly because of acidic parent materials (sandstone origin), and intense weathering led to leaching losses of bases (calcium, magnesium, potassium, and sodium) be ascribed the high-intensity rainfall in this humid region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0515">Patiram, 2007</ce:cross-ref>). Significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher pH in the surface than the subsurface soils across land uses might be from the continuous replenishment of bases from the relatively higher accumulation of organic C in the region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib34" id="crosref0520">Sahoo et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Forest soils were more acidic (by 0.5–1.1 units) than the cultivated land uses in the entire profile depth, probably due to more organic acids production from higher SOC accumulation throughout soil profile depth (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0525">Moges et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). The prevailing anaerobic condition led reduction process and released more hydroxyl ions in the lowland paddy agriculture might have neutralized the soil acidity (pH &gt; 6.0) in the soil profile (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib36" id="crosref0530">Sahrawat, 2004</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0130">Effects of land use conversion on C forms (contents, stocks, and pools)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">Like many other areas, the conversion of land use system and vegetation composition played a significant role in altering soil C forms in the EHR of India (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0535">Sarkar et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0540">Lungmuana et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0545">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). As we hypothesized, accordingly, the forests (DFC) followed by woody horticulture (WHF) were presented with significantly higher amounts of TC, TOC, and C pools (C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">L</ce:inf>, C<ce:inf loc="post">LL</ce:inf>, and C<ce:inf loc="post">NL</ce:inf>). This is in line with the assumption that the C content in the region (except intermontane valleys, <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0550" refid="bib8">Choudhury and Mandal, 2021</ce:cross-ref>) is largely influenced by land use mediated C inputs like biomass accumulation in above (litter and crop residues deposition) and below (root biomass and root exudates) grounds (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0555">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Conversely, C losses depend on the accumulation of biomass/residues turnover and decomposition rate. Limited anthropogenic interference allows abundant biomass accumulation and deposition of organic matter on decomposition in forests intermixed with patches of shrubs (<ce:italic>Brachiaria ruziziensis, Eupatorium odoratum, etc.</ce:italic>) and grasses in the region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0560">Lal, 2004</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0565">Choudhury et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Factors responsible for a differential rate of C accumulation in different land use systems in these mountainous subtropical soils were the quality and quantity of litter return to the soil. As a result, the long-term conversion of virgin forest cover to tree-based land uses and seasonal crop cultivation responded differently to C accumulation (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0570">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0575">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). In our studied soil, the contribution of TIC (content: 0.28–0.56 %) to TC (content: 2.33–3.97 %) was 12.0–14.0 % and TOC was 86–88 % in the top 0.45 m mean depth under three land uses (forests, <ce:italic>Parkia</ce:italic> based AFS - LAF, and lowland paddy). In comparable agroecological conditions (acidic soil, sub-humid climate, hill ecosystem, 17–41 years old similar land use practices, etc.) of adjoining Hilly state (Mizoram) of EHR, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0580">Sahoo et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> also reported comparable contribution (9–10 %) of TIC (content: 0.16–0.31 %) and TOC (89–91 %) to the TC (content: 1.78–3.05 %) in the corresponding soil depth and land uses.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">The potential of the agroforestry system (AFS) in C-sequestration has been well documented across agro-climatic regions. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib42" id="crosref0585">Srinivasarao et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> reported that even with short rotation of eucalyptus and <ce:italic>Leucaena</ce:italic> plantations under a semi-arid environment can sequester carbon to an extent of 10 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. In the humid subtropical region with high rainfall intensity in the study area, the extent of the organic C-sequestration potential of the AFS (&gt;20.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 0.15 soil depth) is much higher (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0590">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). We also observed leguminous agroforestry (LAF) and woody horticulture (WHF) systems with minimum soil disturbances had substantially higher depth distribution of organic C, stock, and pools vertically from the surface till 1.0 depth subsurface soils than the seasonal crop-based land uses (NHF, ALS, and AUS). This might be attributed to the presence of the natural forest vegetation (<ce:italic>Albizia</ce:italic>), leguminous trees like <ce:italic>Alder, Parkia</ce:italic> (in LAF), and citrus fruit trees (in WHF) since these trees produce a significant amount of total root biomass (4.2–8.4 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) including active fine roots at the rate of 3.2–6.3 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> annually in the region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0595">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Significantly higher soil C forms vertically in the soil profile under woody fruit based system (WHF) might be contributed by the biomass addition (above and below ground) from mango and citrus fruit trees. Mango tree produces on an average of 45 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> total above ground biomass and 15 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> underground root biomasses in the Indian Himalaya (Western) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib32" id="crosref0600">Rathore et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) while citrus adds nearly 8.0 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> total root biomasses including 4.2 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> active fine roots in the studied region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0605">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Significantly higher soil carbon forms in the surface soils of the forest and tree-based systems (WHF and LAF) than the deeper soil layers (L4-L6) might be partially from the direct contribution of high litter fall, with very high biomass to necromass ratio (2–3), which encourages faster decomposition and accumulation of C in the surface soil. In addition, 38–47 % fine root biomasses are concentrated in the upper 0.10 m surface soil and 46–51 % of coarse roots are concentrated in the top 0.20 m soil depth (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0610">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Higher accumulation of C by the AFS and their deep root systems improved the cohesiveness and soil aggregation against erosion (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0615">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0620" refid="bib24">Meetei et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Like our leguminous AF (LAF, mostly <ce:italic>Parkia roxburghii</ce:italic> G. Don.), other workers from the region also reported that <ce:italic>Parkia</ce:italic>-based system improves soil enrichment through nitrogen fixation (117–235 kg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and native phosphorus solubilization by root exudation. This system accumulates organic matter into the soil through the addition of fine root biomass at the rate of 3.0–4.0 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> year<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0625">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0630" refid="bib24">Meetei et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">Frequent soil disturbances in the form of weed biomass removal, tillage activities, continuous C mining from the removal of crop residues and burning <ce:italic>in-situ</ce:italic> (a major issue in the study area) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib33" id="crosref0635">Roy et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) might have caused loss of top fertile soils by surface runoff and erosion (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0640">Choudhury et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) in the sloping upland agriculture (AUS) and non-woody horticulture (NHF). This might be responsible for declining C concentration and stock in the cultivated undulating uplands (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0645">Choudhury et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). In lowland agriculture, the prevailing anaerobic conditions resulted in more accumulation of organic C from slow oxidation, local relief allowed deposition of wash-out fertile soils from the cultivated uplands, and decomposition of paddy biomass (straw and roots) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0650">Choudhury et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). However, lesser C-forms including C pools and stocks in lowland agriculture than the forest may be attributed to intensive long periods of cultivation practices, limitation of vertical root distribution (90 % is confined in top 0.20 m depth) resulting from the compacted subsurface soil layer (&gt;0.15 m depth) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0655">Choudhury and Singh, 2013</ce:cross-ref>), and continuous nutrient mining. Similarly, in the Western Himalayan foothills region of India (Siwaliks), <ce:cross-ref refid="bib39" id="crosref0660">Sharma et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> also reported significantly higher oxidizable SOC stocks in the 0.0–0.5 m depth of forest soils (47.5 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) followed by woody fruit-based horticulture (WHF: citrus/mango orchard, 42.4 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) than the maize/wheat-mustard-based upland agriculture system (35.1 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">Management practices play a pivotal role in determining organic C contents in the soil (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0665">Lal, 2004</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib42" id="crosref0670">Srinivasarao et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0675">Maharjan et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Our study showed that land use change was mainly responsible for significant (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0·05) variation in C forms in the soil profile. We found a substantial decrease in the vertical distribution of C forms along with soil depth across land uses. A similar observation of a considerable decrease in labile pools and SOC stocks from the surface (0.0–0.15 m) to subsurface (0.30–0.50 m) soil layers in the forest and cultivated land uses were observed by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib39" id="crosref0680">Sharma et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> in the Western Himalayan foothills of India. This may be attributed to maximum litter fall and plant residues associated with surface soils, which show the inter-linkage with an accumulation and storage of C as compared to sub-surface soils (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0685">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0690">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Climate and soil type including differences in soil orders also considerably influence the distribution of soil C forms. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0695">Srinivasarao et al. (2009)</ce:cross-ref> also reported wide variability (CV: 21.1–53.4 %) in estimated total carbon (organic and inorganic) stock of four major soil orders under rainfed agricultural production systems in the tropical region (arid/semiarid to sub-humid) of India. The greater total C stock (up to 1.05 m depth) was measured in Vertisols (mean of 224.5 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), followed by Inceptisols (114.5 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), Alfisols (57.6 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), and Aridisols (41.1 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>). Our study area represents sub-tropical humid climate (annual rainfall &gt;1800 mm) and soils were classified under the order Inceptisols (Mollic Haplaquepts, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib38" id="crosref0700">Sen et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">The estimated profile TC stock (1.0 m depth) across land uses were considerably higher (mean ± SD: 256.8 ± 57.9 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) with wide variability (191.3–358.8 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) than the reported TC stock (mean ± SD: 114.5 ± 52.4 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) for comparable soil order (Inceptisols) in the tropical (sub-humid) region of India (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0705">Srinivasarao et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>). Even for comparable agricultural land uses (lowland-ALS and upland-AUS rice-based systems) under the same Inceptisols, the estimated TC stock in our study area was substantially higher (mean TC stock: 191.3–259.5 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) than in the tropical region of India (mean TC stock: 52.1–144.9 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0710">Srinivasarao et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>). Higher TC stocks in our studied soils were mainly contributed by many folds higher organic C than in the tropical soils of India. This was evident from the measured organic C content by comparable method (Walkley and Black) for surface (0.0–0.15 m) soil (SOC &gt;1.50 %) against the tropical region (SOC &lt;0.60 %) of India (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0715">Srinivasarao et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>). From a spatial variability mapping of C, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib9" id="crosref0720">Choudhury et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref> also reported that &gt;93 % surface soils (0.15 m depth) of 2.22 million hectare area of Manipur (present study area falls) had Walkley and Black SOC contents &gt;1.5–3.5 % with 50 % soils had SOC stocks of 30–50 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Our measured (by Carbon-Sulfur analyzer) TOC contents (&gt;1.5 to &gt;3.0 %) for profile soils (1.0 m weighted mean) also indicated a very high organic C content (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl3" id="crosref0725">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">Of the TC stock in our rice based land use (ALS and AUS), 69.8 %–84.1 % were contributed by organic C stock (TOC: 133–218 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), while the remaining (15.8–30.1 %) were contributed by inorganic C stock (TIC) (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl3" id="crosref0730">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>). The corresponding contribution by TOC was only 22.5–57.2 %, while 42.8–77.5 % by TIC in the tropical (Subhumid) region of mainland India having comparable land use (rice-based) and soil order (Inceptisol) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0735">Srinivasarao et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>). A similar trend of TIC dominancy over TOC in the TC stocks were also observed in the other three soil orders across the tropical (arid/semiarid to sub-humid) region of India. This deviation is partly attributed to a slower decomposition rate of organic C under the relatively low temperature, acid igneous parent materials, and low calcium and magnesium ions in the highly leached (bases) strong acid (pH &lt; 5.5) soils of humid hill ecosystems of the Eastern Himalayan region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0740">Patiram, 2007</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">Stratification Ratio (SR) of TOC and C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> across land uses were influenced by three ways: (i) land uses (forests and WHF) with higher content in the surface (L1) and as well as in the underlying subsurface soils (L2-L5) had relatively lower SR ratios, (ii) land uses (LAF and NAF) with substantially higher content in the surface than the subsurface soils had higher SRs, and (iii) land uses (AUS, ALS, and NHF) with lower contents in both the surface and the underlying subsurface layers had low SRs. SRs also indicated that forest soils had higher soil C accumulation including labile pool and relatively uniform vertical distribution in the deeper subsurface soil layers than the cultivated tree (except WHF) and seasonal crop-based land uses. Wang et al. (2010) observed that soil organic carbon content decreased with soil depth irrespective of the land use and the values were significantly different among the soil depths. Surface soil (0.0–0.15 m) accounted for only 15 % of the total depth studied (0.0–1.0 m), while contributed nearly double of the sub surface (0.15–1.0 m) TOC contents (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0745">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>b). Irrespective of factors of variations, the addition of organic matter usually occurs on the surface of the soils (Jobbagy and Jackson, 2000). In the surface soils, TOC contents were higher than the bottom-most layers (0.80–1.0 m) of the profile by different magnitudes. Wide variation in SR5 (surface TOC vs. bottom layers TOC contents) further confirmed that the vertical distribution of profile TOC contents strongly influenced by differential land use systems (<ce:cross-refs refid="fig2 fig3" id="crosrefs0025">Figs. 2 and 3</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Vertical distribution pattern also affirmed that forests followed by WHF and LAF had significantly higher C accumulation than seasonal crop-based land uses. A very high amount of C<ce:inf loc="post">VL</ce:inf> in surface (average 41.7 %) and sub-surface soils (34.5 %) across land uses entails constant availability of easily decomposable biomass (living biomass, fine particles of detritus, polysaccharides, and non-humic substances) throughout the years (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib45" id="crosref0750">Tirol-Padre and Ladha, 2004</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0755">Sarkar et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0760">Sahoo et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Higher active C (&gt;53 %) allocation of TOC indicated higher sensitivity of C to land use changes. Naturally, forests maintained a significantly higher quantity (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) of all C pools vertically. Leguminous AF system (<ce:italic>Parkia</ce:italic> spp.) promoted more C in the active form than other cultivated land uses, probably from continuous N-fixing ability and deposition of finer root (hairs) biomass. Cultivation of seasonal crops (vegetables in NHF and paddy agriculture) along the sloppy uplands caused a decline in the active C pool while increased the passive C pool. This signifies that seasonal crop cultivations are more susceptible to loss of readily available C through erosion and topsoil losses from the repeated soil disturbances in this high rainfall receiving region. Surface soils across land use had more active C pools than passive C pools, which indicate faster oxidation, decomposition, and mineralization in the surface than the subsurface soils. However, more passive C pools in subsurface soil may help in the retention of C for longer periods by preventing losses through oxidation and efflux, runoff, and erosion.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0135">Impact of land use conversion on SMBC and enzymatic activities</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">Soil microbial biomass carbon (SMBC) is the labile pool of soil organic C and it is the source of available nutrients to plants and microorganisms (Anderson and Domsch, 1989). The SMBC content increased with TOC content (correlation, r = +0.744), which induced higher soil enzyme (DHA and APA) activities (SMBC vs. enzyme, r = + 0.779 to 0.793). The higher C content in the soil provides the energy source for microbes, thereby increases the SMBC and soil enzyme activity (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib49" id="crosref0765">Wallenius et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0770">Lungmuana et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). This indicates that both the microbial biomass C and enzyme activities are good indicators of soil quality (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib2" id="crosref0775">Bergstrom et al., 1998</ce:cross-ref>). Higher addition of C-substrate and soil microbes through enhanced input of leaf litter and root biomass, exudates into the soils of forests, LAF and WHF is also attributed to higher SMBC and soil enzymes (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0780">Lungmuana et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib17" id="crosref0785">Heintz-Buschart, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The vertical distribution of microbial properties was also affected on the conversion of forest to cultivation, probably due to the decline in C input deposition from the land use mediated addition of plant residues including root biomass (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0790">Dhyani and Tripathi, 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0795">Maharjan et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0800" refid="bib24">Meetei et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Low SMBC and poor soil enzyme activity in the soil profile from seasonal crop cultivation was attributed to the overall reduction in C forms including labile C. Nevertheless, the decrease in soil microbial biomass and enzymatic activities along with the soil depths might be attributed to a consistent decrease in soil C forms (TC, TOC, C-pools) in deeper depths (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib19" id="crosref0805">Lagomarsino et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0810">Lungmuana et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, the microbial properties in the region may be considered in environmental risk assessments and models as indicators of ecosystem disturbance caused by land use conversion and management practices like other regions.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.4" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0140">The effects of land use conversion on soil degradation threats</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">Due to the decline in soil C forms, microbial biomass C and soil enzymatic activities coupled with an increase in compaction on the conversion of forests to cultivation, the resultant cumulative DI values also declined significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) at different magnitudes in the surface (L1) and subsurface soil layers (L2-L6) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig7" id="crosref0815">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig7"/>). The extent of degradation was more severe on the surface than subsoil across cropland. Surface soils of seasonally crop cultivated uplands (AUS &gt; NHF: DI of −559 to −623 %) were more degraded than the tree-based cultivated land uses (NAF &gt; LAF &gt; WHF: DI of-243 to −317 %) and the severity of degradation continued till 0.60 m depth (L4, DI: −420 to −445 %) in AUS and NHF while the reverse trend from immediate subsurface layer (L2, DI: −188 to −307 %) was observed in tree-based land uses. Seasonally cultivated lowlands (ALS) were significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) more resilient to degradation than the uplands (AUS and NHF) but inferior to tree-based land uses. Among the tree-based land uses, woody horticulture (WHF) followed by leguminous agroforestry (LAF) were significantly better in relative resilience to degradation (L1-L6: surface till 1.0 m depth) than the non-leguminous agroforestry (NAF) based land uses, while among the seasonally cultivated land uses, upland paddy (AUS) followed by vegetables (NHF) were more susceptible to degradation till top 0.6 m depth than the more resilient subsurface soils (L3-L6: &gt;0.45 m depth till 1.0 m) of lowland paddy field (ALS) (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig7" id="crosref0820">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>). The study shows that on conversion of primary forests to either tree-based or seasonal crop cultivations, surface soils (L1) were more susceptible to degradation. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib46" id="crosref0825">Tolimir et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> also reported that conversion of 100-years old primary deciduous oak forests to unmanaged agricultural cultivation in the Kolubara River valley of Serbia significantly degraded the soil properties including a decline (by &gt;26 %) in soil organic matter (SOM), increased the compaction (&gt;40 %) by reducing soil porosity, and decline in rheological (plasticity and water content) properties, more intense reduction in surface (0.0–0.15 m) than the subsurface soils.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">We observed a significant reduction in total C (weighted mean of 1.0 m depth: 16.9–37.9 % in tree-based and 38.5–50.2 % in seasonal crops) on the conversion of forests to cultivated land uses. Similarly, C forms and microbial properties (SMBC, DHA, and APA) also declined at different magnitudes: more intense in seasonal crops (except lowland) than tree-based land uses in the soil profile. Human alteration of natural forests into agriculture and other land use causes a drastic decline in soil fertility as well (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib27" id="crosref0830">Mulugeta et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib15" id="crosref0835">Gebresamuel et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). The magnitude of the decline of SOM, however, depends on several factors like climate (rainfall, temperature), soil type, texture, organic matter source, sampling depth, choice of crops or trees, cultivation, and management practices (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib46" id="crosref0840">Tolimir et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Annual inter-crop cultivation of turmeric, ginger, and pineapple in tree-based land uses (WHF, LAF, NAF) and seasonal crop cultivations of paddy and vegetables (AUS, NHF, and ALS) involve tillage and repeated pulverization associated with intercultural operations. Tillage increases aeration and fastens the rate of oxidation of soil organic C, which in turn causes a decline in organic carbon forms (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib40" id="crosref0845">Šimansky et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). However, the severity of decline in SOM was compensated in tree-based land uses by the continuous accumulation of decomposable SOM from the leaf litters, and deep root biomass addition. In contrast, seasonal crops are cultivated with intense tillage operation including wet tillage (in ALS) more frequently and the removal of crop residues or even burning of residues (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib33" id="crosref0850">Roy et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) with a shallow rooting system of field crops (rice/vegetables including pea) intensified the decline in SOM. Therefore, the conversion of natural forest to seasonal crop cultivation in the sloping uplands in the region accelerated the deterioration of soil properties particularly soil C forms than the tree-based land uses (LAF and WHF). The significant beneficial role of SOM in controlling soil processes and functioning, sustainability of soil health (physical, chemical, and biological), soil quality, and land productivity is well known (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0855">Choudhury et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0860" refid="bib8">Choudhury and Mandal, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). With the decline in SOM from unsustainable seasonal crop cultivation particularly in the sloping uplands of tropical mountain soils, all these processes and functions are affected. This deteriorates soil quality, increases the soil susceptibility to surface runoff and erosion and thus, accelerates the soil degradation rate, which is a common phenomenon in the Eastern Himalayan hill agriculture (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0865">Choudhury et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0870" refid="bib8">Choudhury and Mandal, 2021</ce:cross-ref>) including undulating uplands of Nepal Himalaya (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib3" id="crosref0875">Burton et al., 1989</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, the tree-based leguminous agroforestry and woody horticultural fruits may be promoted to sustain land productivity, while assuring food security from the limited cultivable uplands in the foothills of Eastern Himalayan India.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec5" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0145">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">The findings of the study conclude that soils in the study area have developed from homogeneous base materials and similar soil-forming processes since the depth distribution of particle sizes, soil textural class (sandy clay loam), and soil reaction (acidic, pH: 4.68–6.27) were comparable. Differences in the vertical distribution of soil properties, including C-forms and changes to C-mediated microbial properties were, thus attributed to the conversion of forests (&gt;45 years) into long-term (18–25 years) cropland (tree-based and seasonal crops) and related management practices.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">Following significant observations from the study support the hypothesis –</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">Forest had significantly (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) higher C forms (TC, TOC, TIC, and C pools) including microbial properties in the soil profile. Conversion of forests to cultivated land use caused a decline in C forms, labile C pool, and soil microbial properties, a more intense decline was observed in seasonal crop-based (ALS &gt; NHF &gt; AUS) than the tree-based land uses (LAF ≥ WHF &gt; NAF). Among the tree-based land uses, non-leguminous agroforestry (NAF) registered more decline in labile C pool (−44 %) than the leguminous agroforestry (LAF: −16.0 %), and woody horticulture (WHF: −19.3 %) over forest soil. The vertical distribution of C forms decreased steadily with an increase in the depth of the soil profile for all land uses. The degradation index (DI) also confirmed that surface soils in seasonal cropland (AUS &gt; NHF: DI of −559 to −623 %) were more degraded than tree-based land uses. (NAF &gt; LAF &gt; WHF: DI of −243 to −317 %). The severity of the degradation in the AUS and NHF continued down to 0.60 m (L4: 0.45–0.60 m, DI: 420-445 %). Subsurface soil properties (&gt;0.30 m depth) in tree-based LAF and WHF were more resilient to degradation.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">For an effective C sequestration program and improved soil quality, while meeting the food needs of the region from limited cultivable areas, we suggest agroforestry of legumes and woody horticulture (fruits) as potential alternative land uses of sloping uplands while paddy agriculture of lowlands for large intermontane valleys than highly degrading existing upland agriculture of Eastern Himalaya and other similar regions.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec6" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0150">Credit author statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">
                     <ce:list id="olist0010">
                        <ce:list-item id="o0010">
                           <ce:label>1.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">M. A. A and Ch. B M: Planned the framework, executed the experiment, periodic observation, collection of data (soil, plant), laboratory analysis of soil properties, C-pool analysis.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="o0015">
                           <ce:label>2.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">BUC: Carried out statistical analysis of data, written the first draft, edited, and revised version.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="o0020">
                           <ce:label>3.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">SM: Preparing parts of first draft and revision, estimated stratification ratio, degradation index.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="o0025">
                           <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">SLJ: Laboratory analysis of carbon (TOC, TC, and TIC) in PC controlled Carbon-Sulfur analyzer.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                     </ce:list>
                  </ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0010" view="all">
